[[File:Cat carrying kitten (cropped).jpg|thumb|A cat carrying a kitten]] '''Pinch-induced behavioral inhibition''' ('''PIBI''') or '''clipnosis''' is a partially inert state which results from a gentle squeeze of the skin behind the [[neck]]. It is mostly observed among [[Felidae]] and allows the mother cat to easily carry her kitten with her jaws. It can be used to effectively restrain most cats in a domestic or veterinary context.<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 18222719 | year = 2008 | author1 = Pozza | first1 = M. E. | title = Pinch-induced behavioral inhibition ('clipnosis') in domestic cats | journal = Journal of Feline Medicine & Surgery | volume = 10 | issue = 1 | pages = 82-7 | last2 = Stella | first2 = J. L. | last3 = Chappuis-Gagnon | first3 = A. C. | last4 = Wagner | first4 = S. O. | last5 = Buffington | first5 = C. A. | doi = 10.1016/j.jfms.2007.10.008 }}</ref>
