[[File:Koneko Exterior.png|thumbnail|right|Koneko's exterior]]
Koneko ("kitten" in Japanese) is a [[cat cafe]] located on the [[Lower East Side]] of [[Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/blog/omg-new-york-is-getting-a-second-cat-cafe-next-month-080615|title=OMG: New York is getting a second cat café next month|work=Time Out New York|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> The cafe's format is based on Japanese cat cafes, and positions itself as "America's first Japanese Cat Cafe."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/08/fashion/at-a-cat-cafe-sipping-and-purring.html|title=At a Cat Cafe, Sipping and Purring |date=8 November 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> Koneko is partnered with Anjellicle Cats Rescue, a non-profit rescue organization based in [[New York City]] that specializes in pulling cats from the city's [[animal euthanasia | euthanasia shelters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anjelliclecats.com/|title=anjelliclecats.com|publisher=|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> All of the [[felines]] at Koneko are adoptable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3987579/new-york-city-second-cat-cafe/|title=Second Cat Cafe Opening in New York City|author=Olivia B. Waxman|work=TIME.com|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>
Koneko was founded by Benjamin Kalb, a chef who worked previously at [[Bouley]] and [[Momofuku Noodle Bar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2015/08/06/new_les_cat_cafe.php|title=NYC's Newest Cat Cafe Has An Outdoor Garden & Will ALSO Serve Alcohol|work=Gothamist|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Charities based in New York (state)]] [[Category:2015 establishments in New York (state)]] [[Category:Cats]] [[Category:Animal welfare organizations based in the United States]] [[Category:Japanese culture]]

'''Purringtons Cat Lounge''' (sometimes '''Purrington's Cat Lounge''' or simply '''Purringtons'''), is a [[cat café]] located in [[Portland, Oregon]], in the United States. The establishment bills itself as "the first cat cafe and adoption center in the Pacific Northwest".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://purringtonscatlounge.com/home/ |title=Purringtons Cat Lounge |publisher=Purringtons Cat Lounge |date=2016-07-12 |accessdate=2016-07-16}}</ref>

==Description and history==
Purringtons opened on January 24, 2015 at 3529 Northeast Martin Luther King Blvd. in the [[Boise, Portland, Oregon|Boise]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-32725-a-look-inside-purringtons-portlands-first-cat-cafe-video.html |title=A Look Inside Purringtons, Portland's First Cat Cafe (VIDEO) - Willamette Week |website=Wweek.com |date=2015-01-20 |accessdate=2016-07-16}}</ref> More than 300 people attended its opening.<ref name=OPB>{{cite web|last=Lackey |first=Kayo |url=http://www.opb.org/artsandlife/article/oregons-first-cat-cafe-a-look-inside-purringtons-cat-lounge/ |title=Oregon's First Cat Cafe: A Look Inside Purringtons Cat Lounge . Arts & Life |website=OPB.org |date= |accessdate=2016-07-16}}</ref> The business is owned by Kristen and Sergio Castillo. Kristen was inspired to create Purringtons in October 2013, after seeing her friend share a video from Le Café des Chats in Paris.<ref name=OPB/> The business has partnered with the [[Sherwood, Oregon|Sherwood]]-based rescue organization Cat Adoption Team (CAT) to facilitate cat adoptions.<ref name=OPB/>

